    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Jeff can walk comfortably at <m>3</m> miles per hour.
          Find a linear function <m>d</m> that represents the total distance Jeff can walk in <m>t</m> hours,
          assuming he doesn't take any breaks.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>d(t) = 3t</m>, <m>t \geq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Carl can stuff <m>6</m> envelopes per <em>minute</em>.
          Find a linear function <m>E</m> that represents the total number of envelopes Carl can stuff after <m>t</m> <em>hours</em>,
          assuming he doesn't take any breaks.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>E(t) = 360t</m>, <m>t \geq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A landscaping company charges
          <m>\dollar45</m> per cubic yard of mulch plus a delivery charge of <m>\dollar20</m>.
          Find a linear function which computes the total cost <m>C</m>
          (in dollars)
          to deliver <m>x</m> cubic yards of mulch.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>C(x) = 45x+20</m>, <m>x \geq 0</m>.
        </p>
