    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A local pizza store offers medium two-topping pizzas delivered for <m>\dollar6.00</m> per pizza plus a
          <m>\dollar1.50</m> delivery charge per order.
          On weekends, the store runs a <q>game day</q> special:
          if six or more medium two-topping pizzas are ordered,
          they are <m>\dollar5.50</m> each with no delivery charge.
          Write a piecewise-defined linear function which calculates the cost <m>C</m>
          (in dollars)
          of <m>p</m> medium two-topping pizzas delivered during a weekend.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>{\displaystyle C(p) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl} 6p + 1.5 \amp \mbox{ if } \amp 1 \leq p \leq 5 \\ 5.5p \amp \mbox{ if } \amp p\geq 6 \end{array} \right. }</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A restaurant offers a buffet which costs <m>\dollar15</m> per person.
          For parties of <m>10</m> or more people,
          a group discount applies, and the cost is <m>\dollar12.50</m> per person.
          Write a piecewise-defined linear function which calculates the total bill <m>T</m> of a party of <m>n</m> people who all choose the buffet.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>{\displaystyle T(n) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl} 15n \amp \mbox{ if } \amp 1 \leq n \leq 9 \\ 12.5n \amp \mbox{ if } \amp n \geq 10 \end{array} \right. }</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A mobile plan charges a base monthly rate of
          <m>\dollar10</m> for the first <m>500</m> minutes of air time plus a charge of <m>15</m>\textcent for each additional minute.
          Write a piecewise-defined linear function which calculates the monthly cost <m>C</m>
          (in dollars)
          for using <m>m</m> minutes of air time.
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>HINT:</em> You may want to revisit <xref ref="piecewisemobile">Exercise</xref>
          in <xref ref="FunctionNotation">Section</xref>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>{\displaystyle C(m) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl} 10 \amp \mbox{ if } \amp 0 \leq m \leq 500 \\ 10+0.15(m-500) \amp \mbox{ if } \amp m > 500 \end{array} \right. }</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The local pet shop charges <m>12</m>\textcent per cricket up to 100 crickets,
          and <m>10</m>\textcent per cricket thereafter.
          Write a piecewise-defined linear function which calculates the price <m>P</m>,
          in dollars,
          of purchasing <m>c</m> crickets.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>{\displaystyle P(c) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl} 0.12c \amp \mbox{ if } \amp 1 \leq c \leq 100 \\ 12 + 0.1(c-100) \amp \mbox{ if } \amp c > 100 \end{array} \right. }</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The cross-section of a swimming pool is below.
          Write a piecewise-defined linear function which describes the depth of the pool, <m>D</m>
          (in feet)
          as a function of:

          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                the distance
                (in feet)
                from the edge of the shallow end of the pool, <m>d</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                the distance
                (in feet)
                from the edge of the deep end of the pool, <m>s</m>.
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Graph each of the functions in (a) and (b).
                Discuss with your classmates how to transform one into the other and how they relate to the diagram of the pool.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>

        <p>
          <image source="figures/LinearQuadraticGraphics/LinearFunctions-15"></image>
